structure_basic.content:
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════
  Basic Syntax Rules
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════

OVERVIEW:
EBS uses a C-like syntax with clear structural rules.
Understanding these basics is essential for writing EBS programs.

▸ STATEMENTS
───────────────────────────────────────────────────────
• All statements must end with a semicolon (;)
• Multiple statements can appear on a single line
• Semicolons are mandatory, not optional
• Statements can span multiple lines for readability

EXAMPLE 1 - Basic Statements:
<pre>
  var x: int = 10;
  var y: int = 20;
  var sum: int = x + y;
  print "The sum is: " + sum;
</pre>

EXAMPLE 2 - Multiple Statements Per Line:
<pre>
  var a: int = 5; var b: int = 10; var c: int = a + b;
  print "a = " + a; print "b = " + b; print "c = " + c;
</pre>

EXAMPLE 3 - Multi-line Statements:
<pre>
  var longMessage: string = "This is a very long message " +
                            "that spans multiple lines " +
                            "for better readability";
  print longMessage;
</pre>

▸ COMMENTS
───────────────────────────────────────────────────────
• Single-line comments start with //
• Everything after // on the line is ignored
• Use comments to explain your code
• No multi-line comment syntax (use multiple //)

EXAMPLE - Comments:
<pre>
  // This is a single-line comment
  var count: int = 0;  // Initialize counter to zero

  // The following code calculates the total
  // by multiplying price and quantity
  var price: double = 19.99;
  var quantity: int = 3;
  var total: double = price * double(quantity);

  // print "Debug info";  // This line is commented out
</pre>

▸ CODE BLOCKS
───────────────────────────────────────────────────────
• Blocks are enclosed in curly braces { }
• Used for functions, conditionals, and loops
• Blocks define variable scope
• Proper indentation improves readability (not required)

EXAMPLE - Code Blocks:
<pre>
  if x > 10 then {
      // This is a block
      var message: string = "x is greater than 10";
      print message;
  }

  while count < 5 do {
      // Another block
      print "Count: " + count;
      count = count + 1;
  }

  // Nested blocks
  if isActive then {
      if hasPermission then {
          print "Access granted";
      } else {
          print "No permission";
      }
  }
</pre>

▸ CASE SENSITIVITY
───────────────────────────────────────────────────────
• EBS is case-sensitive
• Variable names: myVar, myvar, MyVar are all different
• Keywords must be lowercase: var, if, while (not VAR, IF, WHILE)
• Function names are case-sensitive

EXAMPLE - Case Sensitivity:
<pre>
  var userName: string = "Alice";
  var username: string = "Bob";      // Different variable!
  var UserName: string = "Charlie";  // Also different!

  print userName;   // Output: Alice
  print username;   // Output: Bob
  print UserName;   // Output: Charlie
</pre>

▸ WHITESPACE
───────────────────────────────────────────────────────
• Whitespace (spaces, tabs, newlines) is mostly ignored
• Use whitespace for readability
• At least one space required between keywords and identifiers
• Indentation is conventional but not enforced

EXAMPLE - Whitespace Usage:
<pre>
  // Compact (valid but hard to read)
  var x:int=10;if x>5 then{print"yes";}

  // Readable (recommended style)
  var x: int = 10;
  if x > 5 then {
      print "yes";
  }

  // Extra whitespace (also valid)
  var   y   :   int   =   20   ;
</pre>

▸ STATEMENT TYPES
───────────────────────────────────────────────────────

1. Declaration Statements:
<pre>
  var x: int = 10;
  const PI: double = 3.14159;
</pre>

2. Assignment Statements:
<pre>
  x = 20;
  message = "Hello";
</pre>

3. Expression Statements:
<pre>
  print "Hello, World!";
  call file.writeTextFile("data.txt", content);
</pre>

4. Control Flow Statements:
<pre>
  if condition then { ... }
  while condition do { ... }
  foreach item in list do { ... }
</pre>

5. Return Statements:
<pre>
  return value;
  return;
</pre>

EXAMPLE - Complete Program with Various Statements:
<pre>
  // Variable declarations
  var count: int = 0;
  var items: array[*] = array[*];
  const MAX_ITEMS: int = 100;

  // Add items to array
  items.push("apple");
  items.push("banana");
  items.push("orange");

  // Iterate through items
  foreach item in items do {
      count = count + 1;
      print count + ". " + item;
  }

  // Conditional logic
  if count < MAX_ITEMS then {
      print "Can add more items";
  } else {
      print "Maximum capacity reached";
  }

  // Function call
  print "Total items: " + count;
</pre>

BEST PRACTICES:
• Always end statements with semicolons
• Use meaningful variable names
• Add comments to explain complex logic
• Use consistent indentation (2 or 4 spaces)
• Keep lines reasonably short (< 80-100 characters)
• Group related statements together
• Add blank lines between logical sections

structure_variables.content:
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════
  Variables and Constants
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════

OVERVIEW:
Variables store data that can change during program execution.
Constants store values that cannot be modified after initialization.

▸ VARIABLE DECLARATION
───────────────────────────────────────────────────────
SYNTAX:
<pre>
  var variableName: type = value;
  var variableName = value;  // Type inferred
</pre>

KEY POINTS:
• Use 'var' keyword to declare variables
• Variable names must start with letter or underscore
• Can contain letters, numbers, and underscores
• Type annotation is optional (type inference available)
• Must be initialized when declared

EXAMPLE 1 - Basic Variable Declarations:
<pre>
  // With explicit type annotations
  var name: string = "Alice";
  var age: int = 25;
  var salary: double = 75000.50;
  var isActive: bool = true;

  // With type inference
  var city = "New York";     // Inferred as string
  var count = 42;            // Inferred as int
  var price = 19.99;         // Inferred as double
  var enabled = false;       // Inferred as bool
</pre>

EXAMPLE 2 - Complex Type Variables:
<pre>
  // Array variable
  var numbers: array[5] = array[5];
  var items: array[*] = array[*];

  // JSON variable
  var config: json = {"theme": "dark", "fontSize": 12};

  // Record variable
  var person: record {name: string, age: int};
  person = {"name": "Bob", "age": 30};

  // Bitmap variable
  var flags: bitmap {enabled: 0, active: 1};
</pre>

▸ VARIABLE ASSIGNMENT
───────────────────────────────────────────────────────
• Variables can be reassigned after declaration
• Assignment uses the = operator
• Type must match original declaration (if specified)

EXAMPLE - Variable Reassignment:
<pre>
  var counter: int = 0;
  print "Initial: " + counter;  // Output: Initial: 0

  counter = 10;
  print "Updated: " + counter;  // Output: Updated: 10

  counter = counter + 5;
  print "Final: " + counter;    // Output: Final: 15

  // String reassignment
  var message: string = "Hello";
  message = message + " World";
  print message;  // Output: Hello World
</pre>

▸ TYPE ANNOTATIONS
───────────────────────────────────────────────────────
Supported primitive types:
• int / integer - 32-bit integer
• long - 64-bit integer
• byte - 8-bit integer
• float - 32-bit floating point
• double - 64-bit floating point
• bool / boolean - true or false
• string - text data
• date - date and time

Supported complex types:
• array - fixed or dynamic arrays
• json - JSON objects and arrays
• record - structured data with named fields
• bitmap - bit fields in a byte
• intmap - bit fields in an integer

EXAMPLE - Various Type Annotations:
<pre>
  // Primitive types
  var id: int = 1001;
  var timestamp: long = 1234567890000;
  var flag: byte = 1;
  var temperature: float = 98.6;
  var price: double = 29.99;
  var active: bool = true;
  var label: string = "Product";
  var created: date = call date.now();

  // Collection types
  var scores: array[10] = array[10];
  var data: json = call json.jsonFromString("{}");
</pre>

▸ TYPE INFERENCE
───────────────────────────────────────────────────────
• Compiler infers type from initial value
• Reduces verbosity while maintaining type safety
• Type is fixed once inferred

EXAMPLE - Type Inference:
<pre>
  var x = 42;              // Inferred as int
  var y = 3.14;            // Inferred as double
  var name = "Alice";      // Inferred as string
  var items = array[*];    // Inferred as array[*]

  // x = "text";  // ERROR: Cannot assign string to int
  x = 100;        // OK: int to int

  // Type is determined by first assignment
  var value = 10;     // int
  value = 20;         // OK
  // value = 3.14;    // ERROR: Cannot assign double to int
</pre>

▸ CONSTANTS
───────────────────────────────────────────────────────
SYNTAX:
<pre>
  const CONSTANT_NAME: type = value;
</pre>

KEY POINTS:
• Use 'const' keyword to declare constants
• Must be initialized at declaration
• Cannot be reassigned after initialization
• Convention: Use UPPERCASE names
• Type annotation required

EXAMPLE - Constants:
<pre>
  // Mathematical constants
  const PI: double = 3.14159265359;
  const E: double = 2.71828182846;

  // Application constants
  const APP_NAME: string = "MyApp";
  const VERSION: string = "1.0.0";
  const MAX_USERS: int = 1000;
  const DEBUG_MODE: bool = true;

  // Using constants
  var radius: double = 5.0;
  var area: double = PI * radius * radius;
  print "Area: " + area;

  // PI = 3.14;  // ERROR: Cannot reassign constant
</pre>

▸ VARIABLE SCOPE
───────────────────────────────────────────────────────
• Variables declared in a block are local to that block
• Variables outside blocks are global
• Inner blocks can access outer block variables
• Inner variables shadow outer variables with same name

EXAMPLE - Variable Scope:
<pre>
  // Global variable
  var globalCount: int = 0;

  if true then {
      // Local to this block
      var localCount: int = 10;

      // Can access global variable
      globalCount = 5;

      print "Local: " + localCount;    // OK
      print "Global: " + globalCount;  // OK
  }

  print "Global: " + globalCount;  // OK: 5
  // print localCount;  // ERROR: localCount not in scope
</pre>

EXAMPLE - Variable Shadowing:
<pre>
  var x: int = 10;
  print "Outer x: " + x;  // Output: Outer x: 10

  if true then {
      var x: int = 20;  // Shadows outer x
      print "Inner x: " + x;  // Output: Inner x: 20
  }

  print "Outer x again: " + x;  // Output: Outer x again: 10
</pre>

▸ VARIABLE NAMING CONVENTIONS
───────────────────────────────────────────────────────
• Use camelCase for variable names: myVariable, userName
• Use UPPERCASE for constants: MAX_SIZE, PI
• Choose descriptive names: totalPrice not tp
• Avoid single-letter names except for loops: i, j, k
• Don't use reserved keywords: var, if, while, etc.

EXAMPLE - Good vs. Bad Names:
<pre>
  // Good names (descriptive and clear)
  var userAge: int = 25;
  var totalPrice: double = 99.99;
  var isAuthenticated: bool = false;
  var customerNames: array[*] = array[*];

  // Avoid (too short or unclear)
  var a: int = 25;           // What is 'a'?
  var tp: double = 99.99;    // What is 'tp'?
  var flag: bool = false;    // Flag for what?
  var arr: array[*];         // Array of what?
</pre>

EXAMPLE - Complete Program with Variables:
<pre>
  // Application configuration
  const APP_TITLE: string = "Data Processor";
  const MAX_RECORDS: int = 1000;

  // Global state
  var recordCount: int = 0;
  var totalProcessed: int = 0;
  var hasErrors: bool = false;

  // Function that uses variables
  processData(fileName: string) {
      // Local variables
      var fileContent: string = call file.readTextFile(fileName);
      var lines: array = call str.split(fileContent, "\n");
      var lineCount: int = lines.length;

      // Update global state
      recordCount = lineCount;
      totalProcessed = totalProcessed + lineCount;

      // Check against constant
      if recordCount > MAX_RECORDS then {
          print "Warning: Exceeds maximum records";
          hasErrors = true;
      }

      print "Processed " + lineCount + " records";
  }

  // Main program
  print APP_TITLE;
  call processData("data.txt");
  print "Total processed: " + totalProcessed;
</pre>

BEST PRACTICES:
• Always initialize variables when declared
• Use const for values that don't change
• Choose descriptive variable names
• Minimize global variables when possible
• Use type annotations for clarity in complex code
• Keep variable scope as narrow as possible
• Group related variable declarations together

structure_operators.content:
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════
  Operators
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════

OVERVIEW:
Operators perform operations on values and variables.
EBS supports arithmetic, comparison, logical, and assignment operators.

▸ ARITHMETIC OPERATORS
───────────────────────────────────────────────────────
+   Addition (also string concatenation)
-   Subtraction
*   Multiplication
/   Division
%   Modulo (remainder)

EXAMPLE 1 - Basic Arithmetic:
<pre>
  var a: int = 10;
  var b: int = 3;

  var sum: int = a + b;         // 13
  var difference: int = a - b;  // 7
  var product: int = a * b;     // 30
  var quotient: int = a / b;    // 3 (integer division)
  var remainder: int = a % b;   // 1 (modulo)

  print "Sum: " + sum;
  print "Difference: " + difference;
  print "Product: " + product;
  print "Quotient: " + quotient;
  print "Remainder: " + remainder;
</pre>

EXAMPLE 2 - Floating Point Arithmetic:
<pre>
  var x: double = 10.5;
  var y: double = 2.5;

  var sum: double = x + y;      // 13.0
  var diff: double = x - y;     // 8.0
  var prod: double = x * y;     // 26.25
  var quot: double = x / y;     // 4.2

  // Modulo works with doubles too
  var mod: double = x % y;      // 0.5
</pre>

EXAMPLE 3 - String Concatenation:
<pre>
  var firstName: string = "John";
  var lastName: string = "Doe";
  var fullName: string = firstName + " " + lastName;
  print fullName;  // Output: John Doe

  // Concatenate with numbers (auto-conversion)
  var age: int = 25;
  var message: string = "Age: " + age;
  print message;  // Output: Age: 25
</pre>

▸ COMPARISON OPERATORS
───────────────────────────────────────────────────────
==  Equal to
!=  Not equal to
<   Less than
>   Greater than
<=  Less than or equal to
>=  Greater than or equal to

Comparison operators return boolean values (true or false).

EXAMPLE 1 - Numeric Comparisons:
<pre>
  var x: int = 10;
  var y: int = 20;

  var isEqual: bool = (x == y);      // false
  var notEqual: bool = (x != y);     // true
  var lessThan: bool = (x < y);      // true
  var greaterThan: bool = (x > y);   // false
  var lessOrEqual: bool = (x <= y);  // true
  var greaterOrEqual: bool = (x >= y); // false

  print "x == y: " + isEqual;
  print "x < y: " + lessThan;
</pre>

EXAMPLE 2 - String Comparisons:
<pre>
  var name1: string = "Alice";
  var name2: string = "Bob";

  if name1 == "Alice" then {
      print "Name is Alice";
  }

  if name1 != name2 then {
      print "Names are different";
  }

  // Lexicographic comparison
  if name1 < name2 then {
      print "Alice comes before Bob alphabetically";
  }
</pre>

EXAMPLE 3 - Comparisons in Conditions:
<pre>
  var age: int = 18;
  var score: int = 85;

  if age >= 18 then {
      print "You are an adult";
  }

  if score >= 90 then {
      print "Grade A";
  } else if score >= 80 then {
      print "Grade B";
  } else if score >= 70 then {
      print "Grade C";
  } else {
      print "Grade F";
  }
</pre>

▸ LOGICAL OPERATORS
───────────────────────────────────────────────────────
and  Logical AND (both conditions must be true)
or   Logical OR (at least one condition must be true)
not  Logical NOT (inverts the boolean value)

EXAMPLE 1 - AND Operator:
<pre>
  var age: int = 25;
  var hasLicense: bool = true;

  // Both conditions must be true
  if age >= 18 and hasLicense then {
      print "You can drive";
  }

  var x: int = 15;
  if x > 10 and x < 20 then {
      print "x is between 10 and 20";
  }
</pre>

EXAMPLE 2 - OR Operator:
<pre>
  var isWeekend: bool = false;
  var isHoliday: bool = true;

  // At least one condition must be true
  if isWeekend or isHoliday then {
      print "Day off!";
  }

  var role: string = "admin";
  if role == "admin" or role == "moderator" then {
      print "You have elevated permissions";
  }
</pre>

EXAMPLE 3 - NOT Operator:
<pre>
  var isLoggedIn: bool = false;

  // Invert the boolean value
  if not isLoggedIn then {
      print "Please log in";
  }

  var hasError: bool = false;
  if not hasError then {
      print "Success! No errors detected";
  }
</pre>

EXAMPLE 4 - Complex Logical Expressions:
<pre>
  var age: int = 25;
  var income: double = 50000.0;
  var creditScore: int = 720;
  var hasDebt: bool = false;

  // Complex condition with multiple operators
  if (age >= 21 and age <= 65) and 
     (income > 30000.0 or creditScore > 700) and 
     not hasDebt then {
      print "Loan approved";
  } else {
      print "Loan denied";
  }
</pre>

▸ ASSIGNMENT OPERATOR
───────────────────────────────────────────────────────
=   Assignment (assigns value to variable)

EXAMPLE - Assignment:
<pre>
  var x: int = 10;    // Initial assignment
  x = 20;             // Reassignment

  var y: int = x;     // Assign value of x to y

  var sum: int = x + y;  // Assign result of expression
</pre>

▸ OPERATOR PRECEDENCE
───────────────────────────────────────────────────────
Operators are evaluated in order of precedence (highest to lowest):

1. Parentheses: ()
2. not
3. *, /, %
4. +, -
5. <, >, <=, >=
6. ==, !=
7. and
8. or

EXAMPLE - Operator Precedence:
<pre>
  var result: int = 10 + 5 * 2;  // 20 (multiplication first)
  var result2: int = (10 + 5) * 2;  // 30 (parentheses first)

  var a: int = 5;
  var b: int = 10;
  var c: int = 15;

  // Without parentheses
  var check1: bool = a < b + c;  // true (5 < 25)

  // With parentheses for clarity
  var check2: bool = (a + b) < c;  // false (15 < 15)

  // Complex expression
  var x: bool = (a < b) and (b < c) or (a == 5);
  // Evaluated as: ((a < b) and (b < c)) or (a == 5)
  // Result: (true and true) or true = true
</pre>

▸ OPERATOR USAGE WITH DIFFERENT TYPES
───────────────────────────────────────────────────────

Integers:
<pre>
  var a: int = 10;
  var b: int = 3;
  var div: int = a / b;     // 3 (integer division, no decimal)
  var mod: int = a % b;     // 1 (remainder)
</pre>

Floating Point:
<pre>
  var x: double = 10.0;
  var y: double = 3.0;
  var div: double = x / y;  // 3.3333... (decimal result)
</pre>

Mixed Types (automatic conversion):
<pre>
  var i: int = 10;
  var d: double = 3.5;
  // Automatic conversion to double
  var result: double = double(i) + d;  // 13.5
</pre>

Strings:
<pre>
  var s1: string = "Hello";
  var s2: string = "World";
  var combined: string = s1 + " " + s2;  // "Hello World"

  // String comparison
  var isEqual: bool = (s1 == "Hello");  // true
  var isBefore: bool = (s1 < s2);       // true (lexicographic)
</pre>

Booleans:
<pre>
  var flag1: bool = true;
  var flag2: bool = false;
  var both: bool = flag1 and flag2;     // false
  var either: bool = flag1 or flag2;    // true
  var inverted: bool = not flag1;       // false
</pre>

EXAMPLE - Complete Program Using Operators:
<pre>
  // Constants for grading
  const PASS_GRADE: int = 70;
  const HONOR_GRADE: int = 90;

  // Student data
  var studentName: string = "Alice";
  var score1: int = 85;
  var score2: int = 92;
  var score3: int = 88;

  // Calculate average
  var total: int = score1 + score2 + score3;
  var average: double = double(total) / 3.0;

  print "Student: " + studentName;
  print "Average: " + average;

  // Determine grade status
  if average >= HONOR_GRADE then {
      print "Honor Roll!";
  } else if average >= PASS_GRADE then {
      print "Passing";
  } else {
      print "Needs Improvement";
  }

  // Check consistency
  var consistent: bool = (score1 >= PASS_GRADE) and 
                         (score2 >= PASS_GRADE) and 
                         (score3 >= PASS_GRADE);

  if consistent then {
      print "All scores above passing grade";
  }

  // Check for any high scores
  var hasHighScore: bool = (score1 >= HONOR_GRADE) or 
                           (score2 >= HONOR_GRADE) or 
                           (score3 >= HONOR_GRADE);

  if hasHighScore then {
      print "At least one excellent score!";
  }
</pre>

BEST PRACTICES:
• Use parentheses to make operator precedence explicit
• Break complex expressions into smaller parts
• Use meaningful variable names for boolean expressions
• Be consistent with spacing around operators
• Avoid overly complex expressions - split them up
• Use logical operators to combine related conditions
• Be aware of integer vs floating-point division

structure_functions.content:
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════
  Functions
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════

OVERVIEW:
Functions are reusable blocks of code that perform specific tasks.
They can accept parameters and return values.

▸ FUNCTION DECLARATION
───────────────────────────────────────────────────────
SYNTAX:
<pre>
  functionName(param1: type, param2: type) return returnType {
      // function body
      return value;
  }

  // Function without return value
  functionName(param1: type, param2: type) {
      // function body
  }
</pre>

KEY POINTS:
• No 'function' keyword - just start with function name
• Parameters have type annotations
• Return type specified with 'return' keyword (optional)
• Functions without return type return null implicitly
• Must use 'return' statement to return values

EXAMPLE 1 - Simple Functions:
<pre>
  // Function with return value
  add(a: int, b: int) return int {
      return a + b;
  }

  // Call the function
  var sum: int = call add(10, 20);
  print "Sum: " + sum;  // Output: Sum: 30

  // Function without return value
  greet(name: string) {
      print "Hello, " + name + "!";
  }

  call greet("Alice");  // Output: Hello, Alice!
</pre>

EXAMPLE 2 - Functions with Multiple Parameters:
<pre>
  // Calculate rectangle area
  calculateArea(width: double, height: double) return double {
      var area: double = width * height;
      return area;
  }

  // Calculate rectangle perimeter
  calculatePerimeter(width: double, height: double) return double {
      return 2.0 * (width + height);
  }

  // Use the functions
  var w: double = 5.0;
  var h: double = 10.0;

  var area: double = call calculateArea(w, h);
  var perimeter: double = call calculatePerimeter(w, h);

  print "Area: " + area;          // Output: Area: 50.0
  print "Perimeter: " + perimeter; // Output: Perimeter: 30.0
</pre>

EXAMPLE 3 - Function with Conditional Logic:
<pre>
  // Determine grade from score
  getGrade(score: int) return string {
      if score >= 90 then {
          return "A";
      } else if score >= 80 then {
          return "B";
      } else if score >= 70 then {
          return "C";
      } else if score >= 60 then {
          return "D";
      } else {
          return "F";
      }
  }

  var studentScore: int = 85;
  var grade: string = call getGrade(studentScore);
  print "Grade: " + grade;  // Output: Grade: B
</pre>

▸ CALLING FUNCTIONS
───────────────────────────────────────────────────────
• Use 'call' keyword to invoke functions
• Pass arguments in order of parameters
• Can use function result in expressions
• Can ignore return value if not needed

EXAMPLE - Function Calls:
<pre>
  multiply(a: int, b: int) return int {
      return a * b;
  }

  // Direct call with result usage
  var result: int = call multiply(5, 7);

  // Call in expression
  var total: int = call multiply(3, 4) + call multiply(2, 5);

  // Call without using result
  call multiply(10, 10);  // Result discarded

  // Call with nested function calls
  var nested: int = call multiply(call add(2, 3), 4);
</pre>

▸ FUNCTION SCOPE AND VARIABLES
───────────────────────────────────────────────────────
• Parameters are local to the function
• Variables declared in function are local
• Functions can access global variables
• Local variables shadow global ones with same name

EXAMPLE - Function Scope:
<pre>
  // Global variable
  var globalCounter: int = 0;

  // Function that uses local and global variables
  processItem(itemName: string) {
      // Local variable
      var itemCount: int = 1;

      // Access and modify global variable
      globalCounter = globalCounter + itemCount;

      print "Processing: " + itemName;
      print "Items processed: " + globalCounter;
  }

  call processItem("Apple");
  call processItem("Banana");
  print "Total: " + globalCounter;  // Output: Total: 2
</pre>

▸ RECURSIVE FUNCTIONS
───────────────────────────────────────────────────────
• Functions can call themselves
• Useful for problems with recursive structure
• Must have base case to prevent infinite recursion

EXAMPLE 1 - Factorial:
<pre>
  factorial(n: int) return int {
      // Base case
      if n <= 1 then {
          return 1;
      }

      // Recursive case
      return n * call factorial(n - 1);
  }

  var result: int = call factorial(5);
  print "5! = " + result;  // Output: 5! = 120
</pre>

EXAMPLE 2 - Fibonacci:
<pre>
  fibonacci(n: int) return int {
      // Base cases
      if n <= 1 then {
          return n;
      }

      // Recursive case
      return call fibonacci(n - 1) + call fibonacci(n - 2);
  }

  // Print first 10 Fibonacci numbers
  for var i = 0 to 9 {
      var fib: int = call fibonacci(i);
      print "F(" + i + ") = " + fib;
  }
</pre>

▸ FUNCTIONS WITH COMPLEX TYPES
───────────────────────────────────────────────────────
• Functions can accept and return arrays, JSON, records
• Pass complex types by reference

EXAMPLE - Array Parameter:
<pre>
  // Calculate sum of array elements
  sumArray(numbers: array) return int {
      var total: int = 0;
      foreach num in numbers do {
          total = total + num;
      }
      return total;
  }

  var scores: array[5] = array[5];
  scores[0] = 85;
  scores[1] = 92;
  scores[2] = 78;
  scores[3] = 90;
  scores[4] = 88;

  var sum: int = call sumArray(scores);
  print "Total: " + sum;  // Output: Total: 433
</pre>

EXAMPLE - JSON Parameter:
<pre>
  // Process user data
  displayUser(user: json) {
      var name: string = call json.getString(user, "name", "Unknown");
      var age: int = call json.getInt(user, "age", 0);
      var email: string = call json.getString(user, "email", "N/A");

      print "Name: " + name;
      print "Age: " + age;
      print "Email: " + email;
  }

  var userData: json = {"name": "Alice", "age": 30, "email": "alice@example.com"};
  call displayUser(userData);
</pre>

EXAMPLE - Return Array:
<pre>
  // Generate array of squares
  generateSquares(count: int) return array {
      var squares: array[*] = array[*];
      for var i = 1 to count {
          var square: int = i * i;
          squares.push(square);
      }
      return squares;
  }

  var squareNumbers: array = call generateSquares(5);
  foreach num in squareNumbers do {
      print num;  // Output: 1, 4, 9, 16, 25
  }
</pre>

▸ FUNCTION ORGANIZATION
───────────────────────────────────────────────────────
• Define functions before use (or at top of file)
• Group related functions together
• Use descriptive function names (verbs)
• Keep functions focused on single task

EXAMPLE - Complete Program with Functions:
<pre>
  // ===== Math Utility Functions =====

  isEven(number: int) return bool {
      return (number % 2) == 0;
  }

  isPrime(number: int) return bool {
      if number < 2 then {
          return false;
      }

      for var i = 2 to number - 1 {
          if (number % i) == 0 then {
              return false;
          }
      }

      return true;
  }

  findPrimes(max: int) return array {
      var primes: array[*] = array[*];
      for var i = 2 to max {
          if call isPrime(i) then {
              primes.push(i);
          }
      }
      return primes;
  }

  displayResults(numbers: array, label: string) {
      print label;
      foreach num in numbers do {
          print "  " + num;
      }
      print "Count: " + numbers.length;
  }

  // ===== Main Program =====

  const MAX_NUMBER: int = 20;

  // Find all primes up to MAX_NUMBER
  var primeNumbers: array = call findPrimes(MAX_NUMBER);
  call displayResults(primeNumbers, "Prime numbers up to " + MAX_NUMBER + ":");

  // Check specific numbers
  var testNumber: int = 17;
  if call isPrime(testNumber) then {
      print testNumber + " is prime";
  }

  if call isEven(testNumber) then {
      print testNumber + " is even";
  } else {
      print testNumber + " is odd";
  }
</pre>

BEST PRACTICES:
• Use descriptive function names (calculateTotal, not calc)
• Keep functions short and focused
• Add comments to explain complex logic
• Use consistent naming conventions
• Avoid deep nesting - extract to helper functions
• Return early when possible to reduce nesting
• Test functions with various inputs
• Consider edge cases and validation

structure_imports.content:
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════
  Imports
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════

OVERVIEW:
Imports allow you to organize code across multiple files.
Code from imported files becomes available in the importing file.

▸ IMPORT SYNTAX
───────────────────────────────────────────────────────
SYNTAX:
<pre>
  import "filename.ebs";
  import "path/to/file.ebs";
  import "../relative/path/file.ebs";
</pre>

KEY POINTS:
• Use 'import' keyword followed by file path in quotes
• Path is relative to the current file's location
• File extension .ebs is required
• Imports are processed at parse time
• All functions and global variables from imported file are available
• Circular imports are not allowed (A imports B, B imports A)

EXAMPLE 1 - Basic Import:

File: math_utils.ebs
<pre>
  // Math utility functions
  add(a: int, b: int) return int {
      return a + b;
  }

  multiply(a: int, b: int) return int {
      return a * b;
  }

  const PI: double = 3.14159;
</pre>

File: main.ebs
<pre>
  // Import the math utilities
  import "math_utils.ebs";

  // Now we can use functions from math_utils.ebs
  var sum: int = call add(10, 20);
  var product: int = call multiply(5, 7);

  print "Sum: " + sum;        // Output: Sum: 30
  print "Product: " + product; // Output: Product: 35

  // Access imported constant
  var radius: double = 5.0;
  var area: double = PI * radius * radius;
  print "Area: " + area;
</pre>

EXAMPLE 2 - Relative Path Imports:

Project structure:
<pre>
  project/
    main.ebs
    utils/
      string_utils.ebs
      array_utils.ebs
    lib/
      validation.ebs
</pre>

File: main.ebs
<pre>
  // Import from subdirectory
  import "utils/string_utils.ebs";
  import "utils/array_utils.ebs";
  import "lib/validation.ebs";

  // Use imported functions
  var text: string = "hello world";
  var upper: string = call toUpperCase(text);
  print upper;
</pre>

▸ WHAT GETS IMPORTED
───────────────────────────────────────────────────────
• All user-defined functions from imported file
• All global variables and constants from imported file
• Imports from the imported file (transitive imports)
• Does NOT import builtin functions (always available)

EXAMPLE - Complete Multi-File Program:

File: validators.ebs
<pre>
  // Validation utility functions
  isValidEmail(email: string) return bool {
      var atIndex: int = call str.indexOf(email, "@", 0);
      var dotIndex: int = call str.indexOf(email, ".", 0);
      return atIndex > 0 and dotIndex > atIndex;
  }

  isValidAge(age: int) return bool {
      return age >= 0 and age <= 150;
  }
</pre>

File: formatters.ebs
<pre>
  // Formatting utility functions
  formatName(name: string) return string {
      var trimmed: string = call str.trim(name);
      var lower: string = call str.toLower(trimmed);
      var first: string = call str.toUpper(call str.substring(lower, 0, 1));
      var rest: string = call str.substring(lower, 1, lower.length);
      return first + rest;
  }
</pre>

File: main.ebs
<pre>
  import "validators.ebs";
  import "formatters.ebs";

  // Create user
  var userName: string = "alice smith";
  var userAge: int = 25;
  var userEmail: string = "alice@example.com";

  // Validate
  if call isValidAge(userAge) and call isValidEmail(userEmail) then {
      var formattedName: string = call formatName(userName);
      print "User: " + formattedName;
      print "Age: " + userAge;
      print "Email: " + userEmail;
  } else {
      print "Invalid user data";
  }
</pre>

BEST PRACTICES:
• Place all imports at the top of the file
• Use relative paths consistently
• Organize code into logical modules
• Avoid circular dependencies
• Keep imported files focused and cohesive
• Document dependencies in comments
• Use descriptive file and function names
• Test modules independently when possible

flow_conditionals.content:
OVERVIEW:
Conditional statements execute code based on boolean conditions.
Use 'if-then-else' to control program flow.

SYNTAX:
<pre>
  if condition then {
      // code when true
  } else if condition2 then {
      // code when condition2 is true
  } else {
      // code when all conditions are false
  }
</pre>

KEY POINTS:
• Condition must evaluate to a boolean (true/false)
• 'then' keyword is required after condition
• 'else if' allows multiple conditions
• 'else' clause is optional
• Braces { } define code blocks

EXAMPLE 1 - Simple If:
<pre>
  var age: int = 20;
  if age >= 18 then {
      print "You are an adult";
  }
</pre>

EXAMPLE 2 - If-Else:
<pre>
  var temperature: int = 25;
  if temperature > 30 then {
      print "It's hot outside";
  } else {
      print "Temperature is comfortable";
  }
</pre>

EXAMPLE 3 - Multiple Conditions:
<pre>
  var score: int = 85;
  if score >= 90 then {
      print "Grade: A";
  } else if score >= 80 then {
      print "Grade: B";
  } else if score >= 70 then {
      print "Grade: C";
  } else {
      print "Grade: F";
  }
</pre>

EXAMPLE 4 - Complex Conditions:
<pre>
  var age: int = 25;
  var hasLicense: bool = true;
  if age >= 18 and hasLicense then {
      print "You can drive";
  } else if age >= 18 and not hasLicense then {
      print "Get a license first";
  } else {
      print "Too young to drive";
  }
</pre>

flow_loops.content:
OVERVIEW:
Loops execute code repeatedly based on conditions or iterations.
EBS supports while, for, foreach, and do-while loops.

WHILE LOOP:
Executes while condition is true. Condition checked before each iteration.

SYNTAX:
<pre>
  while condition do {
      // code
  }
</pre>

EXAMPLE - While Loop:
<pre>
  var count: int = 0;
  while count < 5 do {
      print "Count: " + count;
      count = count + 1;
  }
  // Output: Count: 0, Count: 1, Count: 2, Count: 3, Count: 4
</pre>

FOR LOOP:
Iterates over a range of values.

SYNTAX:
<pre>
  for var i = start to end {
      // code
  }
</pre>

EXAMPLE - For Loop:
<pre>
  for var i = 1 to 5 {
      print "Iteration: " + i;
  }
  // Output: Iteration: 1, 2, 3, 4, 5
</pre>

FOREACH LOOP:
Iterates over elements in an array or collection.

SYNTAX:
<pre>
  foreach element in collection do {
      // code
  }
</pre>

EXAMPLE - Foreach with Array:
<pre>
  var fruits: array[*] = ["apple", "banana", "orange"];
  foreach fruit in fruits do {
      print "Fruit: " + fruit;
  }
  // Output: Fruit: apple, Fruit: banana, Fruit: orange
</pre>

EXAMPLE - Foreach with JSON Array:
<pre>
  var numbers: json = [10, 20, 30, 40];
  var sum: int = 0;
  foreach num in numbers do {
      sum = sum + num;
  }
  print "Sum: " + sum;  // Output: Sum: 100
</pre>

DO-WHILE LOOP:
Executes at least once, then repeats while condition is true.

SYNTAX:
<pre>
  do {
      // code
  } while condition;
</pre>

EXAMPLE - Do-While Loop:
<pre>
  var input: int = 0;
  do {
      print "Enter a positive number: ";
      input = 5;  // Simulated input
  } while input <= 0;
</pre>

NESTED LOOPS:
Loops can be nested for multi-dimensional iteration.

EXAMPLE - Nested For Loops:
<pre>
  for var row = 1 to 3 {
      for var col = 1 to 3 {
          print "[" + row + "," + col + "]";
      }
  }
</pre>

flow_break_continue.content:
OVERVIEW:
Loop control keywords alter normal loop execution flow.
• break (or exit) - Immediately exits the current loop
• continue - Skips remaining code and starts next iteration

BREAK STATEMENT:
Exits the loop entirely and continues with code after the loop.

SYNTAX:
<pre>
  break;   // or exit;
</pre>

EXAMPLE 1 - Break in While Loop:
<pre>
  var i: int = 0;
  while i < 10 do {
      if i == 5 then {
          print "Breaking at: " + i;
          break;
      }
      print "i = " + i;
      i = i + 1;
  }
  print "Loop ended";
  // Output: i = 0, i = 1, i = 2, i = 3, i = 4, Breaking at: 5, Loop ended
</pre>

EXAMPLE 2 - Break in Foreach:
<pre>
  var numbers: array[*] = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7, 8];
  var found: bool = false;
  foreach num in numbers do {
      if num == 5 then {
          print "Found: " + num;
          found = true;
          break;
      }
  }
  // Stops iterating when 5 is found
</pre>

CONTINUE STATEMENT:
Skips the rest of the current iteration and proceeds to the next one.

SYNTAX:
<pre>
  continue;
</pre>

EXAMPLE 1 - Continue in While Loop:
<pre>
  var i: int = 0;
  while i < 5 do {
      i = i + 1;
      if i == 3 then {
          continue;  // Skip printing when i is 3
      }
      print "Number: " + i;
  }
  // Output: Number: 1, Number: 2, Number: 4, Number: 5
</pre>

EXAMPLE 2 - Continue to Skip Negatives:
<pre>
  var numbers: array[*] = [-2, 3, -1, 5, -4, 8];
  var sum: int = 0;
  foreach num in numbers do {
      if num < 0 then {
          continue;  // Skip negative numbers
      }
      sum = sum + num;
  }
  print "Sum of positives: " + sum;  // Output: Sum of positives: 16
</pre>

EXAMPLE 3 - Continue to Filter:
<pre>
  var items: array[*] = ["apple", "banana", "apricot", "orange", "avocado"];
  print "Items starting with 'a':";
  foreach item in items do {
      var firstChar: string = call str.substring(item, 0, 1);
      if firstChar != "a" then {
          continue;  // Skip items not starting with 'a'
      }
      print "  " + item;
  }
  // Output: apple, apricot, avocado
</pre>

USE CASES:
• break: Exit loop when target is found or condition met
• break: Prevent infinite loops with emergency exit
• continue: Skip invalid/unwanted items in iteration
• continue: Filter data during processing

flow_exceptions.content:
OVERVIEW:
Exception handling catches and manages runtime errors gracefully.
Use try-exceptions to prevent script crashes and handle errors.

SYNTAX:
<pre>
  try {
      // code that might throw an exception
  } exceptions when exceptionVariable {
      // error handling code
      // exceptionVariable contains error message
  }
</pre>

KEY POINTS:
• Wrap risky code in try block
• exceptions keyword starts error handler
• when keyword binds exception to a variable
• Exception variable contains error details as string
• Code continues after exception handler
• Prevents script from crashing on errors

EXAMPLE 1 - File I/O Error Handling:
<pre>
  try {
      var content: string = call file.readTextFile("data.txt");
      print "File content: " + content;
  } exceptions when ex {
      print "Error reading file: " + ex;
      print "Using default data instead";
  }
</pre>

EXAMPLE 2 - Division by Zero:
<pre>
  var numerator: double = 100.0;
  var denominator: double = 0.0;
  try {
      var result: double = numerator / denominator;
      print "Result: " + result;
  } exceptions when error {
      print "Cannot divide by zero: " + error;
      print "Using safe default value";
  }
</pre>

EXAMPLE 3 - Database Connection:
<pre>
  try {
      connect db = "jdbc:mysql://localhost:3306/mydb";
      use db {
          cursor c = select * from users;
          open c();
          while c.hasNext() do {
              var row = c.next();
              print row;
          }
          close c;
      }
      close connection db;
  } exceptions when dbError {
      print "Database error: " + dbError;
      print "Check connection settings";
  }
</pre>

EXAMPLE 4 - JSON Parsing:
<pre>
  var jsonText: string = "{invalid json}";
  try {
      var data: json = call json.jsonFromString(jsonText);
      print "Parsed successfully";
  } exceptions when parseError {
      print "JSON parse error: " + parseError;
      // Use empty JSON object as fallback
      var data: json = call json.jsonFromString("{}");
  }
</pre>

EXAMPLE 5 - Multiple Operations:
<pre>
  var success: bool = false;
  try {
      // Multiple operations that might fail
      var exists: bool = call file.exists("config.json");
      if exists then {
          var config: string = call file.readTextFile("config.json");
          var settings: json = call json.jsonFromString(config);
          print "Configuration loaded";
          success = true;
      }
  } exceptions when ex {
      print "Failed to load config: " + ex;
      print "Using default settings";
  }

  if success then {
      print "Initialization complete";
  }
</pre>

COMMON USE CASES:
• File operations (read, write, delete)
• Database operations (connect, query)
• Network requests (HTTP, FTP)
• JSON parsing and manipulation
• Type conversions that may fail
• Array index access (out of bounds)
• Any builtin function that may fail

BEST PRACTICES:
• Always handle exceptions for I/O operations
• Provide meaningful error messages
• Include fallback behavior when possible
• Log errors for debugging
• Don't catch exceptions silently

screen_data.content:
OVERVIEW:
The 'vars' section defines screen variables that hold data.
Each variable can have a display component for user interaction.

BASIC STRUCTURE:
<pre>
  screen myScreen = {
      "vars": [
          {
              "name": "username",
              "type": "string",
              "default": ""
          },
          {
              "name": "age",
              "type": "int",
              "default": 0
          }
      ]
  };
</pre>

VARIABLE PROPERTIES:
• name - Variable identifier (required)
• type - Data type (string, int, float, double, bool, json, array, etc.)
• default - Initial value
• display - Display component configuration (optional)

SUPPORTED DATA TYPES:
• Primitives: string, int, long, float, double, byte, bool
• Collections: array, json, map
• Complex: record, bitmap, intmap
• Special: date, canvas

ACCESSING DATA:
<pre>
  // Direct property access
  myScreen.username = "Alice";
  print myScreen.username;
</pre>

<pre>
  // Using builtin functions
  call scr.setValue("myScreen", "username", "Bob");
  var name = call scr.getValue("myScreen", "username");
</pre>

EXAMPLE WITH COMPLEX TYPE:
<pre>
  screen dataScreen = {
      "vars": [
          {
              "name": "config",
              "type": "json",
              "default": {"theme": "dark", "size": 14}
          },
          {
              "name": "items",
              "type": "array",
              "default": []
          }
      ]
  };
</pre>

screen_items.content:
OVERVIEW:
Items bind screen variables to display components within areas.
Each item references a variable and is positioned in an area.

BASIC STRUCTURE:
<pre>
  "items": [
      {
          "name": "usernameField",
          "varRef": "username",
          "seq": 1,
          "row": 0,
          "col": 0
      }
  ]
</pre>

ITEM PROPERTIES:

IDENTIFICATION:
• name - Item identifier (required)
• varRef - Variable name to bind (required)
• seq - Sequence number for ordering

POSITIONING (varies by area type):
• row, col - Grid position (gridpane)
• rowSpan, colSpan - Grid cell spanning
• alignment - Item alignment within cell
• relativePos - Relative position (top, bottom, left, right)

SIZING:
• minWidth, prefWidth, maxWidth - Width constraints
• minHeight, prefHeight, maxHeight - Height constraints
• hgrow - Horizontal grow priority
• vgrow - Vertical grow priority

STYLING:
• style - CSS style string
• styleClass - CSS class names

BEHAVIOR:
• editable - Enable/disable editing
• visible - Show/hide item
• disabled - Disable item
• stateful - Track state changes
• mandatory - Required field indicator

EXAMPLE - SIMPLE ITEMS:
<pre>
  "area": [{
      "name": "formArea",
      "type": "vbox",
      "items": [
          {
              "name": "nameField",
              "varRef": "username",
              "seq": 1
          },
          {
              "name": "emailField",
              "varRef": "email",
              "seq": 2,
              "editable": true
          },
          {
              "name": "saveBtn",
              "varRef": "saveButton",
              "seq": 3
          }
      ]
  }]
</pre>

EXAMPLE - GRID ITEMS:
<pre>
  "area": [{
      "name": "gridArea",
      "type": "gridpane",
      "items": [
          {
              "name": "firstNameField",
              "varRef": "firstName",
              "row": 0,
              "col": 1,
              "hgrow": "ALWAYS"
          },
          {
              "name": "lastNameField",
              "varRef": "lastName",
              "row": 1,
              "col": 1,
              "colSpan": 2,
              "hgrow": "ALWAYS"
          }
      ]
  }]
</pre>

EXAMPLE - STYLED ITEMS:
<pre>
  "items": [{
      "name": "titleField",
      "varRef": "title",
      "style": "-fx-font-size: 18px; -fx-font-weight: bold;",
      "styleClass": "header-field",
      "minWidth": "200",
      "prefWidth": "400"
  }]
</pre>

ITEM OPERATIONS:
<pre>
  // Set item property
  call scr.setProperty("myScreen.emailField", "editable", false);
  call scr.setProperty("myScreen.emailField", "visible", true);
  call scr.setProperty("myScreen.emailField", "tooltip", "Enter email");
</pre>

<pre>
  // Get item property
  var editable = call scr.getProperty("myScreen.emailField", "editable");
  var status = call scr.getItemStatus("myScreen", "emailField");
</pre>

<pre>
  // Item data source
  call scr.setItemSource("myScreen", "emailField", "display");
  var source = call scr.getItemSource("myScreen", "emailField");
</pre>

<pre>
  // Reset item
  call scr.resetItemOriginalValue("myScreen", "emailField");
</pre>

<pre>
  // Get all items
  var itemList = call scr.getItemList("myScreen");
  foreach item in itemList {
      print "Item: " + item;
  }
</pre>

ITEM WITHOUT DISPLAY:
Items can reference variables that have no display component:
<pre>
  "vars": [{"name": "hiddenData", "type": "string"}]
  "items": [{"name": "hidden", "varRef": "hiddenData"}]
</pre>

CHOICE OPTIONS:
For combobox, choicebox, listview - set options dynamically:
<pre>
  var options = ["Option 1", "Option 2", "Option 3"];
  call scr.setItemChoiceOptions("myScreen", "myCombo", options);
  var current = call scr.getItemChoiceOptions("myScreen", "myCombo");
</pre>

ITEM VALIDATION:
<pre>
  // Check if screen has changes
  var changed = call scr.checkChanged("myScreen");
</pre>

<pre>
  // Check for errors
  var hasError = call scr.checkError("myScreen");
</pre>

<pre>
  // Set/get screen status
  call scr.setStatus("myScreen", "changed");
  var status = call scr.getStatus("myScreen");
</pre>

<pre>
  // Set/get error message
  call scr.setError("myScreen", "Validation failed");
  var error = call scr.getError("myScreen");
</pre>

